column9: ChatGPT is best for explaining code, debugging, and helping you learn or prototype across many languages. Claude shines when you need to reason over long codebases or discuss high-level architecture with careful, safer suggestions. Gemini is strong at deep reasoning, math-heavy problems, and understanding visuals like diagrams or code screenshots. Copilot excels at day-to-day coding inside your IDE, offering fast autocomplete and boilerplate based on your project context. Used together, Copilot boosts speed, while ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini help you think, design, and debug more effectively.
column10: When I'm handling multiple tasks at once, I rely on a few simple prioritization principles. Triage first – I quickly sort tasks by urgency and impact, so critical blockers get attention before "nice-to-haves." Break tasks down – Large or vague tasks get split into smaller, concrete steps so progress can happen in parallel. Context switching control – I try to batch similar tasks together (e.g., all debugging, all writing) to reduce mental overhead. Progress over perfection – I aim to deliver a solid first pass early, then iterate if time allows. Continuous re-evaluation – As new information comes in, priorities can shift, so I reassess rather than blindly sticking to an old plan.
column11: On a daily basis, I use AI as a thinking partner more than a replacement. It helps me quickly draft, summarize, or reframe information so I can move faster without losing clarity. For technical work, AI is great at spotting bugs, suggesting improvements, and generating first-pass solutions, which I then refine. It's also useful for context switching—if I jump from coding to writing to planning, AI helps me reload the mental state quickly. AI also shines in learning and exploration: breaking down unfamiliar concepts, comparing tools, or explaining tradeoffs so decisions are better informed. And finally, it's a big productivity boost for repetitive or low-leverage tasks (boilerplate, formatting, test cases), freeing up time for creative or strategic thinking.
column12: One example is when I notice a user repeatedly running into the same underlying issue across different questions, even if they don't explicitly ask for a fix. Instead of just answering each question in isolation, I'll step back, identify the root cause (for example, a flawed architecture choice or an inefficient workflow), and proactively suggest a better approach. I'll often include a small refactor, a checklist, or a pattern they can reuse so the problem doesn't keep resurfacing. This usually saves time long-term and prevents future errors, even though it goes beyond the original request. The initiative comes from recognizing that solving the systemic problem is more valuable than solving the immediate symptom.
column13: I start by understanding the tool's purpose and strengths, so I know what problems it's actually meant to solve and don't misuse it. Next, I get hands-on quickly, experimenting with small, real tasks instead of passively reading documentation. As I go, I compare its behavior to tools I already know, which helps me transfer existing mental models and learn faster. I also pay attention to limitations and failure cases, because knowing what not to rely on is just as important as knowing what it does well. Finally, I refine my usage by iterating—adjusting prompts, workflows, or integrations based on real outcomes rather than assumptions.
column14: First, I assess the risk level of the information: high-impact areas (like security, finance, or production code) automatically get stricter validation. Next, I cross-check key claims against trusted sources such as official documentation, specs, or well-maintained repos, rather than relying on a single reference. I then validate through execution or experimentation where possible—running the code, testing edge cases, or reproducing results. I also watch for hallucination signals, like vague citations, inconsistent terminology, or overly confident answers to ambiguous questions. Finally, I treat AI output as a strong draft, not an authority, combining it with human judgment and domain knowledge before acting on it.

column13: When learning a new AI tool or system, I follow a structured and hands-on approach. First, I start by understanding its purpose, what problem it solves. Second, I explore the tool practically. I prefer learning by doing testing features, running small simulations, and observing outputs. Third, I connect it to the real task, apply it to actual work scenarios, and see how it improves efficiency, accuracy, or reporting. My experience in technical support and data analysis has trained me to adapt quickly to a new system and technology. Overall, I approach new AI tools with curiosity, structure, and initiative, ensuring I not only understand how to use them, but also how to maximize their value responsibly and effectively.
column14: To verify AI-generated information, I follow a structured validation process. First, I cross-check the output against reliable and authoritative sources such as official documents, companies' policies, academic references, or trusted database. Second, I access logical consistency and relevance. I review whether the information aligns with known facts, current data, and the specific context of the task. Third, for data-related outputs, I validate the numbers by rechecking the original dataset or recalculating the key features. Fourth, I apply professional judgment. My experience in data analysis and technical support has trained me to identify consistency, biggest statement, and unsupported claims. Lastly, when necessary, I consult subject matter expert or my SME supervisor's DL team leader to confirm critical information before finalizing reports or decisions. I view the AI as a support tool, not a final authority. So verification, critical thinking, and accountability are always part of my process to ensure reliability and quality.

column10: I manage my time when, yes, when multiple tasks are assigned to me at once, I manage my time by organizing and prioritizing my work. First, I list all the tasks and identify which ones are most urgent and more important. This helps me focus on deadlines and avoid last-minute pressure. Next, I create simple schedule or to-do list to plan how much time I will spend on each task. I break bigger tasks into smaller steps so they are easier to handle. I also avoid distractions and stay focused while working to complete tasks efficiently. Lastly, I review my progress regularly and adjust my plan if needed. By staying organized, disciplined, and flexible, I am able to manage my time effectively and complete my tasks on time.

column12: One time, when I took initiative to solve a problem without being instructed was during a group project. column13: When I encounter a new AI tool or system that I am unfamiliar with, I start by exploring its features and interface to understand how it works. I read the guides, tutorials, or watch short videos to quickly learn the basic functions. Next, I practice using the tool hands-on by trying simple tasks first and gradually moving to more advanced features. This helps me learn more effectively and build confidence. If I encounter difficulties, I search for solutions online or ask for help from knowledgeable people.
column14: The steps I will take to verify whether AI-generated information is accurate and reliable to verify whether AI-generated information is accurate and reliable, I cross-check it with trusted sources such as official websites, academic materials, and credible news platforms. this helps confirm the correctness of the information. I also compare the details across multiple sources to see if they are consistent if several reliable references provide the same information, it increases my confidence in its accuracy. Lastly, I apply critical thinking by checking if the information makes sense, is logical, and is free from bias or errors. Through these steps, I ensure that AI-generated content is reliable and trustworthy.
